The dataset is suffering from relatively extreme temporal bias. The absence of "fake news" samples before 2016 and the sudden increase after mid 2017 will likely result in any potential models overfitting on events from specific time periods.

Because of this we should be very careful about using features based on specific keywords or entities.

Semantic Analysis etc.

We've used Spacy and other techniques to generate a set of features based on various semantic and other attributes of each article:

Lexical Features

avg_word_length, lexical_diversity, readability, stop_words_ratio

Measure vocabulary complexity and text readability. Average word length and lexical diversity indicate vocabulary richness, while readability scores (e.g., Flesch Reading Ease) quantify overall text complexity. Stop words ratio reflects the proportion of common functional words, potentially indicating formality or information density.

Syntactic Features

pos_ratio_*, max_dep_depth

Capture grammatical structure. POS ratios show distribution of word types (nouns, verbs, etc.), revealing syntactic patterns. Max dependency depth indicates sentence complexity through nesting of grammatical structures.

Semantic Features

ner_density, avg_token_vector_norm, sentiment

Analyze meaning and content. NER density indicates fact density, average token vector norm (from spaCy's word vectors) suggests semantic richness, and sentiment score captures emotional tone.

Structural Features

avg_sent_length, median_sent_length, std_sent_length, punctuation_density

Describe text organization. Sentence length statistics reveal writing style and complexity. Punctuation density can indicate sentence structure complexity.

Temporal Features

verb_tense_ratio_*

Show time orientation through ratios of past, present, and future tenses. Useful for analyzing narrative focus in news or historical texts.

Entity Features

num_*_entities, *_entities

Identify key subjects. Entity counts and types (Person, Organization, Geopolitical Entity) reveal main text subjects. Top entities indicate key players or themes.

We can see that "fake news" articles have a distinctive linguistic patterns compared to Reuters news reports which is not particularly surprising.

They tend to use more pronouns and adverbs, suggesting a more personal and descriptive style. These articles are less likely to use past tense, potentially focusing more on current or future events.

The sentence structure in fake news is characterized by greater variability in length, but with generally shorter sentences overall. This contrasts with legitimate news, which tends to have more consistent and slightly longer sentences.

Fake news articles often have higher readability scores, indicating simpler language, and shorter average word lengths. They also contain fewer named entities (specific people, places, or organizations), suggesting less detailed or fact-based content.

Interestingly, fake news articles are more likely to include unusual words, symbols, or potential grammatical errors. This could indicate less rigorous editing or a more casual writing style.

Again these findings only apply when comparing again articles published by Reuters specifically and not non "fake" news in general.

If we analyze ratios of specific grammatical elements and word types inside both samples, we see some further distinctions:

  • Fake news uses more interjections and subordinating conjunctions, likely indicating a more emotive style and possibly more complex sentence structures. However, they employ fewer nouns, adpositions, and determiners, suggesting less specific information.

  • They also have higher ratios of spaces and symbols, with slightly more auxiliary verbs, but less punctuation and fewer adjectives. This reinforces the hypothesis of a more informal, emotionally charged style in fake news, with potentially less emphasis on concrete facts compared to Reuters articles.

Embedings and Building a DNN Model

{TODO: improve section name}

A significant problem with the dataset is that it's much too easy to build a robust model while using raw data because a model would significantly overfit on:

  • Articles often include the name of the news agency that published it or very specific patterns e.g. Reuters reports always start in exactly the same way.

e.g. Since almost all non-"fake" articles in this dataset are written by Reuters, and they tend to begin their articles with a very specific pattern e.g.:

Due to all the issues analyzed previously we don't believe that it's possible to build a robust model that could provide any meanginful value by using the dataset directly (or in any way...):

Non-representivie dataset

The main issue is that almost all "non-fake" news articles are published by Reuters while the "fake" come from various different sources:

In[21]:

This means that the legitimate news samples are highly unrrepresntive and only reflect the style of language etc. used by a single organization that gennerally only tends to publish realtivelly unbiased factual news reports with minimal analysis or opinions.

It's likely that other sources (even the ones which have published the "fake news" articles in this dataset) publish at least some "non-fake" stories/articles even though they might be significantly more biased or use a language that's much harder to discern from fake news.

Effectively this means that any model we build will only be able to classify whether an article was published by Retuers or not (i.e. the model will struggle with corecctly classifying any "non-fake" articles written by Reuters".

Temporal Biases

Additional the dataset is also highly non representive temporally:

  1. the number of articles that are included is extremely unenevely distributed in the included period. Morever same applies to the target variable (i.e. most newer articles are "fake" while most older ones come from Reuters).

This means that we can't use the text without removing most specific entity names from it (e.g. persons, organization, locations etc.) e.g.:

  • {the proportion of articles mentioning Hillary Clinton that were fake news varied significantly based on the 2016 eleciton cycle, same applies to many other political figures and events).

  • { e.g. EXPLAIN what do I mean in more abstract way}. Fake news articles mentioning organizations like ISIS had a very high ratio of {FAKE NEWS articles} in the included period, while other groups like Hezbollah or Hamas had a much lower ratios. However this highly depends on the period the samples are coming from and it's possible that it has inverted when ISIS {left the news cycle}.

  • {e.t.c}

Annomyizing text samples

Therefore we chose to focus exclusively on the style and structure of all articles instead of their specific content when preparing inputs for our DNN (BERT based) model:

Since specific proper names (persons, organizations, regions) are very highly associated with fake news articles not because of their inherent attributes due to when the article was published we've removed all proper nouns (specifically "entities" detected by Spacy) and just replaced them with their type:

  1. Each entity is replaced with it's specific tag, e.g. "Kasich" becomes [PERSON0]
  2. Inside the anonymized sample the same enitity retains the same id (e.g. "Kassich is always [PERSON0], Michigan is always "[GPE2]" etc.

The preprocssesing pipeline supports other more complex modes, like assinging unique keywords or hashes (unique to each sample) to each entity so that e.g. 'PERSON{N}' etc. wouldn't be repeated in each article, however we didn't notice a signficant different in classification performance.

Example sample after full transformations:

def get_tsne_for_embeddings(embeddings, perplexity=30, n_iter=1000):
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    scaled_features = scaler.fit_transform(embeddings)

    tsne = TSNE(n_components=2, random_state=42, perplexity=perplexity, n_iter=n_iter)
    tsne_results = tsne.fit_transform(scaled_features)
    return tsne_results

Clustering

UMAP and HDBSCAN were used to cluster the embeddings (512 tokens, with remainder of the text truncated).

The specific number of UMAP components (and HDBSCAN scan parameters) were by hyperparameter tuning and targetting these specific metrics:

  • Silhouette Score
  • Calinski-Harabasz score
  • Penalty based on proportion of noise (samples not included in any cluster)

def compare_clusters_with_target(cluster_columns, target, column_names):
    """
    Compare multiple independent HDBSCAN clustering results with a target variable.
    
    :param cluster_columns: List of Series, each containing HDBSCAN cluster labels
    :param target: Series containing the target variable
    :param column_names: List of names for each clustering column
    :return: DataFrame with comparison metrics
    """
    results = []

    for clusters, name in zip(cluster_columns, column_names):
        results.append({
            'Text Representation': name,
            'Num Clusters': len(np.unique(clusters)),
            'NMI': normalized_mutual_info_score(target, clusters),
            'ARI': adjusted_rand_score(target, clusters)
        })

    return pd.DataFrame(results)

    train_df_2_cluster[f"{target_embedding_columns.raw_text.embedding}_cluster"],
    train_df_2_cluster[f"{target_embedding_columns.processed_text.embedding}_cluster"],
    train_df_2_cluster[f"{target_embedding_columns.anonymized_embeddings.embedding}_cluster"]
]
target = train_df["fake"]
column_names = ['Raw Text', 'Processed Text', 'Anonymized Text']

comparison_df = compare_clusters_with_target(cluster_columns, target, column_names)
comparison_df

NMI (Normalized Mutual Information) measures the amount of information shared between the clustering results and the true labels. It quantifies how well the clustering aligns with the actual categories, accounting for different numbers of clusters.

ARI (Adjusted Rand Index) assesses the similarity between the clustering and true labels, adjusting for chance agreement. It provides a measure of accuracy for the clustering compared to the ground truth, with correction for random labeling.

Both metrics help evaluate clustering performance, with higher values indicating better alignment between the clustering results and the true labels.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score, precision_score, recall_score


def analyze_cluster_target_overlap(cluster_column, target):
    df = pd.DataFrame({'Cluster': cluster_column, 'Target': target})

    results = []
    for c_id in df['Cluster'].unique():
        cluster_mask = df['Cluster'] == c_id
        cluster_data = df[cluster_mask]
        cluster_size = len(cluster_data)
        fake_count = (cluster_data['Target'] == 1).sum()
        fake_proportion = fake_count / cluster_size

        majority_class = 1 if fake_proportion > 0.5 else 0

        # Treat the cluster as a classifier for its majority class
        y_true = (df['Target'] == majority_class).astype(int)
        y_pred = cluster_mask.astype(int)

        precision = precision_score(y_true, y_pred)
        recall = recall_score(y_true, y_pred)
        f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred)

        results.append({
            'Cluster': c_id,
            'Size': cluster_size,
            'Fake_Count': fake_count,
            'Real_Count': cluster_size - fake_count,
            'Fake_Proportion': fake_proportion,
            'Real_Proportion': 1 - fake_proportion,
            'Majority_Class': majority_class,
            'Precision': precision,
            'Recall': recall,
            'F1': f1
        })

    results_df = pd.DataFrame(results).sort_values('Size', ascending=False)

    # Calculate overall statistics
    total_size = results_df['Size'].sum()
    total_fake = results_df['Fake_Count'].sum()
    overall_fake_proportion = total_fake / total_size

    overall_row = pd.DataFrame({
        'Cluster': ['Overall'],
        'Size': [total_size],
        'Fake_Count': [total_fake],
        'Real_Count': [total_size - total_fake],
        'Fake_Proportion': [overall_fake_proportion],
        # 'Real_Proportion': [1 - overall_fake_proportion],
        'Majority_Class': [1 if overall_fake_proportion > 0.5 else 0],
        'Precision': [np.nan],
        'Recall': [np.nan],
        'F1': [np.nan]
    })

    results_df = pd.concat([results_df, overall_row], ignore_index=True)

    return results_df

Our assumption is that these clusters represent more finegrained clusters based on topic or other attributes besides being split around the target variable.

We'll use TF-IDF combined with chi-squared to identifies key terms and overal themes in each cluster. This approach highlights terms that are both frequent and unique to each cluster

  1. TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) identifies potentially important terms in each cluster.

  2. Chi-squared analysis then determines which of these terms are statistically distinctive for each cluster.

  3. Named entity recognition extracts key actors, organizations, and locations from the text.

# Function to merge topics for each row
def merge_topics(row):
    active_entities = [col for col in entity_cols if bool(row[col])]

    row_topics = {}

    for topic, data in topic_analysis.MERGED_TOPICS.items():
        topic_key = f"topic_{topic}"
        if set(active_entities).intersection(data["tags"]):
            row_topics[topic_key] = 1
        else:
            row_topics[topic_key] = 0

    return pd.Series(row_topics)

def generate_entity_wordclouds(df, cluster_column, target_column="fake",
                               entity_prefix=('topic_', 'org_', 'gpe_', 'person_'),
                               top_n=50, distinctiveness_weight=0.5):
    entity_cols = [col for col in df.columns if col.startswith(entity_prefix)]

    grouped = df.groupby(cluster_column)[entity_cols].sum()

    total_occurrences = grouped.sum()
    relative_freq = grouped.div(grouped.sum(axis=1), axis=0)

    avg_relative_freq = relative_freq.mean()

    distinctiveness = relative_freq.div(avg_relative_freq) - 1

    entity_target_props = {}
    for entity in entity_cols:
        entity_mask = df[entity] > 0
        entity_target_props[entity] = df.loc[entity_mask, target_column].mean()

    wordclouds = {}
    scores = {}
    topic_scores = {}

    for cluster in grouped.index:
        cluster_scores = {}
        cluster_topic_scores = {}
        for entity in entity_cols:
            abs_freq = grouped.loc[cluster, entity]
            rel_freq = relative_freq.loc[cluster, entity]
            dist_score = distinctiveness.loc[cluster, entity]

            score = (1 - distinctiveness_weight) * rel_freq + distinctiveness_weight * max(dist_score, 0)

            if entity.startswith("topic_"):
                cluster_topic_scores[entity.split('_', 1)[1]] = score
                continue

            if score > 0:
                cluster_scores[entity.split('_', 1)[1]] = score

        topic_scores[cluster] = cluster_topic_scores
        max_score = max(cluster_scores.values()) if cluster_scores else 1
        normalized_scores = {k: v / max_score for k, v in cluster_scores.items()}

        top_entities = dict(sorted(normalized_scores.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:top_n])

        palette = sns.color_palette("RdBu_r", as_cmap=True)

        def color_func(word, font_size, position, orientation, random_state=None, **kwargs):
            entity_key = next((key for key in entity_target_props if key.endswith(word)), None)
            if entity_key:
                value = entity_target_props[entity_key]
                rgb = palette(value)[:3]  # Get RGB values from the colormap
                return f"rgb({int(rgb[0] * 255)}, {int(rgb[1] * 255)}, {int(rgb[2] * 255)})"
            return "grey"

        wordclouds[cluster] = WordCloud(width=1200, height=600, background_color='white').generate_from_frequencies(
            top_entities)
        wordclouds[cluster] = wordclouds[cluster].recolor(color_func=color_func, random_state=42)

        scores[cluster] = top_entities

    return wordclouds, scores, topic_scores, entity_target_props


def plot_wordcloud(wordcloud, title, topic_scores, entity_target_props):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

    img = ax.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
    ax.axis('off')

    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax)
    cax = divider.append_axes("right", size="5%", pad=0.1)

    cmap = sns.color_palette("RdBu_r", as_cmap=True)

    norm = Normalize(vmin=0, vmax=1)
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=norm)
    sm.set_array([])

    cbar = plt.colorbar(sm, cax=cax)
    cbar.set_label('Usage in Fake (%)')

    top_2_keys = sorted(topic_scores, key=topic_scores.get, reverse=True)[:2]
    top_2_keys = ", ".join([k.replace("_", " ") for k in top_2_keys])
    ax.set_title(f"{title}: {top_2_keys}", loc='left', pad=20, fontsize=15)

    plt.tight_layout(pad=0)
    plt.show()

Cluster Centroid Summarization

This technique generates three key outputs for each text cluster:

Representative text: The document whose embedding is closest to the cluster's centroid (mean embedding), measured by cosine similarity. Keyword list: The most frequent terms in the cluster, excluding stop words, typically 10-20 words ranked by frequency. Cluster size: The number of documents in the cluster.

To use this technique:

Calculate the centroid (mean embedding) for each cluster. Find the document closest to each centroid using cosine similarity. Aggregate all texts in each cluster and extract frequent terms. Count the documents in each cluster.

Interpretation:

Representative text: Provides a concrete example of the cluster's content. Compare across clusters to understand dataset themes. Keywords: Highlight common topics or entities. Look for unexpected combinations or variations between clusters.
